[2
Date: Sat 17 Nov 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agencia EFE (via COMTEX), Sat 17 Nov 2001 [edited

Nicaragua: 2 die from dengue hemorrhagic fever
----------------------------------------------
MANAGUA: This week 2 people died from dengue hemorrhagic fever in
Nicaragua, bringing to 13 the number of deaths related to the disease so
far this year, Health Ministry spokeswoman Tamara Montes said.
The health authorities are concerned about the rise in the number of cases
of dengue hemorrhagic fever compared with this time last year, when only 5
deaths and 96 suspected cases had been reported. At 257, the number of
cases reported so far this year is nearly three time the year-to-date
figure for November 2000. One of those who died this week was a resident of
Managua, which has the highest number of dengue cases in Nicaragua, while
the other death took place in the province of Leon, 90 kilometers (about 55
miles) west of the capital.
Between January and the first week of November, 1481 cases of the more
common classic dengue fever were confirmed, whereas only 759 were
registered in the same period last year, Montes added. According to
ministry officials, another 8516 people suspected of having dengue were
examined in health care centers. The health authorities have recommended
prevention measures for major cities, specifically the elimination of
breeding grounds for the mosquitoes that carry the virus, such as flooded
areas and water containers.
